<br>
What it boils down to is not being able to effectively solo charm kite much of PoP.  IMO, charm is an overpowered ability in this game.  Like many other overpowered abilities in the past (cheal, mod rods, manaburn, now the ranged dps, etc), they've tried to design encounters around it, and ultimately decided it needed to be trimmed down.<br>
<br>
There's a lot in this game that is unbalanced.  Overpowered abilities at times can make the game more fun (from a godlike perspective), less frustrating, less of a timesink, but ultimately make it less challenging.   They also make it easier to overlook the underpowered ones, which hurt the playability of certain classes.  For example, mages were used as mod rod machines for so long, and encounters were designed with their intent as this type of mana supply, that it seemed to me anyway that the rest of their class abilities got swept under the rug by Verant to collect dust.  As a result, mages were only truly fun to play if you had a genuine like of the class in spite of its flaws, and didn't mind casting mod rods all day (and the occasional coh).  Of course, that's the view of an outsider to the mage class so perhaps I'm wrong.<br>
<br>
I'm happy that certain classes got the ability for a powerful charm in PoP.  It certainly looks like the chanter class is a much more compelling class to play than it was at level 60 (and not only for the charm I mean; the new defensive abilities etc are very nice as well, and many of the new encounters are designed around dealing with adds, etc).  But it was making certain aspects of the game too easy.  Plvling a cleric to 65 in a matter of hours, soloing for insanely fast xp, soloing mobs who can still destroy raids with ungodly ease.<br>
<br>
Obviously charm still needs to be looked at; perhaps increasing its power once again, perhaps not.  But whining at Sony for messing with the ability is patently silly imo.  The part of that ability that was unbalanced *WASN'T JUST THE XP GAIN* so of course they should look at other aspects of it.<br>
<br>
Yeah, I know you're ranting, I just wanted to rant back.  Charm was a good draw for those underplayed classes and maybe it should have been kept the way it was.  That's how I feel about bard changes atm.  ;p  Just wanted to state I don't think Sony is soooo evil for trying to &quot;fix&quot; such things as a general rule.<br>
<br>
/hides behind Pedi to avoid Whizbang's wrath for approving of the dreaded manaburn nerf<br>
<br>
~Kat<br>
